text: Okay, our tape recorders are rolling on this end. How long did you know, Howard? I don't remember just exactly when they moved to Cross Plains. It seemed to me like it was around 19 and 20 or 21. And that's when I first became acquainted with him. He was probably 13 years old, something like that at that time. What was he like when he was a little boy? Be your pardon? What was he like when he was a boy at 13? Oh, he was just another kid that just, you know, just average small-town boy. His father was a doctor, you know, just a country doctor. And his mother was Irish, and she liked to use her Irish brogue. You know, she really practiced on that. But Robert was very studious in school. He didn't get out and play with the other kids a lot like most kids do. Yeah, we lived right back by the other side of their house. We lived in the house just east of their house. Do you know when he got interested in writing? No, but it was before he finished high school, and I don't remember just when he finished high school, probably about... well, let's see. Probably about 1923, somewhere along there. But he was already writing those stories. Weird Tales was the magazine that published most of them. Did you read any of them when they came out? no I tried I didn't get interested in them I was well it just wasn't the type of stuff I was interested in I was more interested in the western story type stuff that they published at that time yeah he wrote he wrote some western stories too if I remember correctly did you ever read any of those? I don't remember. I might have. I don't remember. Do you remember if he ever talked much about the stuff he was writing about or if he was kind of closed about that? No, he wasn't close about it or anything. But it's been so long ago that I don't remember. You know, there's been a lifetime in there that's gone by and I just don't remember. Okay. Okay. Do you remember by any chance any stories about Robert? would any particular thing come to mind that was memorable about him? Well, about just his home life, his private life there. He had a, out in the backyard, he always kept a big log there, a tree trunk, you know, and a big sledgehammer. I guess the thing would have weighed 12 or 14 pounds. and he'd get out and for his exercise, for his daily exercise, he would get out there and beat on that log with that big old sledgehammer until have it beat to pieces and he'd get another log. But he was exceptionally strong due to the fact that he exercised with this heavy hammer, you know. and he'd do that well for an hour maybe or longer just beat on that log with that big old heavy sledgehammer then he had a dog just a big old cur dog and his name was Patch P-A-T-C-H and when he was mealtime came and he'd fix up whatever the dog was going to eat and get out in the backyard and start calling the dog. He'd call it Chuck Patch. Chuck Patch, he'd call that a half a dozen times. This old dog would come around wherever he was. As far as I know, he did not own a rifle or a shotgun. He did buy a pistol, and that was the gun he killed himself with. and if I remember right it's been so long ago I think it was a .32-20 caliber Colt I may be wrong about the caliber but I think that's what it was yeah on some of the stuff that I've read I've read a lot of different things one of the people said that some of the people in cross planes had a feeling that Howard was going to commit suicide sometime because of his personality. Did you ever get that impression? What we heard, and my wife and I were in California when he died, and this was in 1936 or 37, somewhere along there, his mother got sick and it was terminal and Robert told his daddy he says I don't want to live after my mother's gone and so when his mother died he went out in the car and sat down and shot himself John K. One of the things we've been trying, of course a lot of people have been trying to figure this out because ours has become rather famous over the years, is why he would have done that. You probably knew him further well. Could you give any speculation as to why he would have gone out and shot himself and his mother died i don't know like i say my wife and i were in california at that time and we had lost contact with them but uh robert never married he never seemed interested in girls and uh he did have one girlfriend there in crossplains for a time i'd see him out in the car driving around once in a while but i don't think that lasted too long, he was just wrapped up in his, in his work, writing those stories. And he had a glassed-end back porch on the southeast side of the house there. And it wasn't too far from my mother's bedroom. And a lot of times at night, he would wake her up with a typewriter clicking, you know, at one and two o'clock in the morning, some inspiration, and he'd probably be laying there in bed and think of something, and he'd get up and write it down right quick. And he just worked all the hours, you know, whenever he'd think of something, he wanted to put in a story. Yeah, that's very interesting. That's very interesting. I don't know. I kind of wondered myself. You know, he did ride a whole lot rather quickly. And I just kind of wonder if he was burning himself out. He could possibly have been. However, the last time I saw him, which was along about 1934, 1935, he seemed in good health. Yeah. About that last time you saw him, what do you remember about that? Well, nothing in particular. Just, you know, we'd say hello across the fence and talk a few minutes. When we were still kids, Francis Bannerman and Sons was a big mail order house in New York that handled all kinds of armaments and things from medieval times on up to modern. And we had ordered a couple of little, and they weren't pinching swords in that sense. I don't know just exactly the name of them, but they had a round hilt on them, you know, where you'd protect your hands. But we ordered those things, and we'd get out in the backyard and wrap a bandana hatch around our heads like a parrot. And we'd get out and fence with those things. Of course, we didn't dare, you know, hit each other with them because they'd have gone through you. But we did that quite a bit. But we had an immense live oak tree in our backyard, and we'd get out there and shade that old tree in. pretend that we were back maybe in the dark ages or something or in the time of the Spanish thing things like that he had things like that on his mind all the time yeah I guess that I guess that sort of with how his imagination worked he had a very vivid imagination yes he did okay let's see um i've about covered all my questions here i didn't want to take up too much of your time He had some relatives in Ranger, Texas. Have you contacted anyone in Ranger? No, sir. There may be. They might have passed away by now. But he had some ants, one or two ants, I believe it was, in Ranger. And they were the only heirs to the Howard Estate there. And they were up until, oh, two or three years ago, I think. Some of them were still living and still drawing bodies, some of his stories that were still being published. Yeah. I've heard of them. We haven't attempted to talk with them. I'm sure DeCamp, is that his name, DeCamp? Yes, sir. I'm sure he contacted them and you'll probably get all that information from him. Yeah. Um... And Jack Scott, as far as I know, is your best authority there in Cross Plains on Robert. Yeah, I've talked to Mr. Scott before. He was quite helpful. he recommended talking to Mr. Scott Baum, and Mr. Scott Baum said, well, you need to call Leroy Butler. He knew him too. So we've been kind of going, you know, from one to the other to the other. And I think we've probably got enough information here. We may call Mr. Scott again to see if he's remembered anything else, because there's going to be probably a lot of publicity or at least some publicity about Howard in conjunction with the movie that's coming out in the latter part of May I do know this during the time of the Depression you know until his death had the best income of anyone in Cross Plains including the bankers and the school teachers and all the other professions there, that Robert's income from his stories was bringing in more money than anybody else in Cross Plains was drawing. Yeah. Yeah, that's interesting. More money than the bunkers, too, huh? Uh-huh. Nobody laughed at those stories, I bet. That's right. Alright, Mr. Butler, I think I've covered anything. I sure do appreciate it. Why, you're quite welcome.
